Implement a pattern extraction module that reviews generated projects and extracts reusable patterns.

The extractor must analyze:

- builder structure
- page files
- section usage
- layout refiner outputs
- final accepted designs

It must identify patterns such as:

- frequently reused sections
- best-performing section order
- visually balanced layout combinations
- recurring responsive fixes
- common text/content structures

The extractor must avoid storing one-off noisy data.

Phase 4 — User Approval Signals

The engine must learn only from useful or approved outcomes.

Signals may include:

- site published
- user kept generated layout
- user made only minor edits
- user accepted refined layout
- component reused multiple times
- page version marked as final

The system must give higher weight to approved patterns and lower weight to discarded ones.

Phase 5 — Integration With Site Planner

The Site Planner must consult the memory engine before generating a new website plan.

Workflow

User prompt
→ detect website type
→ check memory for relevant patterns
→ load previous successful structures
→ combine with current prompt intent
→ generate improved site plan

Example

User prompt

Create website for restaurant

Planner should first look up:

restaurant website patterns

Then propose a stronger structure using learned best practices.

Phase 6 — Integration With Design Intelligence

The Design Intelligence System must also use learned patterns.

It must be able to reuse:

- preferred spacing patterns
- preferred typography scales
- preferred hero compositions
- preferred grid combinations
- preferred image-to-text ratios

This ensures generated sites become more visually consistent and more polished over time.

Phase 7 — Integration With Component Reuse

The memory engine must help component selection.

Example

If the system learned that restaurant homepages commonly perform better with:

HeroSection + GalleryPreview + TestimonialsSection + CTASection

then the planner should prioritize this known-good pattern instead of creating random combinations.

Phase 8 — Learning From Builder Edits

If a user manually adjusts a generated website in the builder, the system must analyze those edits and determine whether they reflect an improvement pattern.

Examples

- user consistently increases section spacing
- user changes all CTA buttons to a specific style
- user replaces compact hero layouts with image-heavy hero layouts

If similar edits happen repeatedly, the engine should learn from them.

Phase 9 — Learning From AI Chat Edits

The engine must also observe AI chat-driven changes.

Examples

- repeated requests to make headings shorter
- repeated requests to simplify layouts
- repeated requests to align sections more consistently
- repeated requests to improve CTA visibility

These recurring edits should become signals for future generations.

Phase 10 — Memory Retrieval Rules

The memory engine must retrieve only relevant patterns.

Relevance factors

- website category
- project type
- number of pages
- layout style
- business niche
- design density
- visual style

Example

A SaaS memory pattern should not be applied directly to a restaurant site unless there is strong similarity.

Phase 11 — Safe Learning Constraints

Do NOT allow memory to cause uncontrolled duplication.
Do NOT allow memory to override current prompt intent.
Do NOT blindly reuse old code.

Memory must be advisory, not destructive.

The current user prompt and current project context must always remain the primary source of truth.

Phase 12 — Versioned Memory

Store memory with version metadata.

Each memory pattern should include:

- source project id
- creation date
- number of successful reuses
- confidence score
- website type
- design style label

This allows ranking and future cleanup.

Phase 13 — Cleanup and Pruning

Implement memory cleanup rules.

Remove or downgrade:

- low-confidence patterns
- outdated patterns
- patterns from discarded projects
- duplicated entries
- irrelevant noisy structures

This prevents the memory system from becoming bloated.

Phase 14 — AI Usage Example

User prompt

Create a modern dental clinic website

System flow

- classify project as medical business website
- retrieve relevant clinic/medical patterns
- reuse known-good page structure
- apply known design rules for trust-focused layouts
- generate website using existing components
- refine layout
- save approved result back into memory

Phase 15 — Logging and Observability

Every learning and retrieval action must be logged.

Logs must include:

- retrieved pattern ids
- applied memory patterns
- ignored memory patterns
- reason for reuse
- confidence score
- timestamp

This ensures transparency and debugging.

Phase 16 — Expected Result

After implementation, Webu AI must improve with usage.

The system must become better at:

- planning websites
- choosing page structures
- selecting sections
- applying design logic
- reusing successful patterns
- producing polished websites faster

This transforms Webu from a one-time AI generator into a learning AI website builder that continuously improves based on successful outputs and user-approved refinements.


